<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. An Account of Lake Superior, 1807-1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0037</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">influence I cannot pretend to say.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The river empties itself into a small bay and has a large sand bank some hundred yards from the entrance.  The beach of this bay is strewed with a great variety of Stones ready shaped for sharpening Scythes and Carpenter's Tools; they are of different figures and some of them of a very fine grit.  The point at each extremity of the bay is a red freestone and from fifty to sixty feet high.  You mount the river for two leagues, at some distance from the entrance it divides into three branches, the middle of which is the shortest and leads you to a Lake of perhaps three leagues in circumference, the water of which is exceedingly black and abound with Sturgeon; the land is extremely high all round it, and towards the Southwestern extremity a small band of Indians have their garden grounds on an elevation of at least sixty feet above the level of the Lake, in as rich a soil as I ever saw.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The Lake narrows away to the westward where you enter a little Serpentine river, which is mounted with much difficulty; you then enter a little marshy Lake of about a mile long, at the farther end of which you have to draw your Canoe through the mud at the risk of having the men mired up to the neck: here you have</p>

